Hacktivism Tiffany Wong Dr. Vladimir Kuperman Societal and Ethical Implication November 16, 2020

We live in a world where through the power of the internet drastic changes in different societies can happen, there is a term coined for it which is “hacktivism”. In the early 2010’s there was a huge wave of hacking that were aimed to help people and empower them in whatever cause they were pursuing, some of these events would probably go down in history as some of the most important and influential things to happen in recent times whether they are “good” or “bad”. What I am going to talk about in this paper is the ethics behind what I believe fundamentally is a good thing but as we know with human nature and past history people find a way to make it destructive and hurtful. First, what is hacktivism? In modern society it is described as the act of using legal or illegal computer-based methods such as DDOS attacks, doxing, leaks for political ends, free speech and to preserve human rights (1). Some examples of notorious incidents include Operation Tunisia in 2011, where anonymous worked with Tunisian hackers and aimed to takedown Tunisian government websites down and this started what later would become the Arab spring. Once people saw the gravity of power this can have and how change that would usually years to happen would happen instantly, more and more hacktivist started appearing and becoming active and each with their own cause in mind. This paper is not only about hacktivism, it is more about the ethics of people taking it into their own hands and using the internet in a request for what could be justice, freedom, anarchy and even sometimes selfish monetary reasons. Since this is a relatively new phenomena it is not easy as to just point to a theory relating to ethics and saying that is the answer, it is blurrier than that. Fundamentally, we all have similar outlook of social construct in the department of acting in a moral way, because we believe it creates peace and reduce social chaos (2). Well it is evident that most cases of hacktivism promote some form of social chaos, so are we to just shun the issue being raised because the means it came from is not socially “ethical” well that is hard to answer because there are a lot of variables that lie in the means and we cannot have an answer that will fit all situations so it is imperative that when attacking anything of this subject we have good critical thinking and the ability form opinions of our own because it could get muddied with other’s and sometimes it is not the most likeable one. So, “when is it OK for outsiders to intervene?”, As we see in the video the hacker group “Anonymous” was the main contributor to the events that happened in Steubenville, Ohio in 2013. The way things unfolded during that time is what I believe the right way to use hacktivism which is using the internet to bring light to an incident and sharing it with people around the world in hopes of achieving change that is morally good. Because the video was released a lot of women came together and courageously shared their experience with sexual assault and this ultimately helped everyone in town realize how unfortunately common it is for women to experience it and also putting pressure on the police to make arrests instead sweeping things under the rug, this eventually lead to a couple of arrests and some school officials being laid off. Now, if every issue that has the potential to be solved this way I believe 100 times out of 100 it should be done in some similar manner but unfortunately not every situation can lead to this type of conclusion. One similar event that happened recently was the #MeToo movement, it is basically the personal reports on widespread sexual assaults committed by influential male figures. What started as a way for female celebrities to call out high ranking executives and accuse them of sexual assault turned into a controversial topic that could affect how men should interact with women. Because with this movement came this idea that men do not know when they are harassing women, and this had a huge effect in recent years whether good or bad in how society views the interactions between male and female. As consequence of this movement, what is viewed as harassment or not especially in a work environment is being challenged on a regular basis these days. Some would argue that this led to men sometimes being afraid to interact with women in fear of being accused of such things, but I believe in most cases men and women agree on what is harassment and what is not (3). My main takeaway from this is how a movement that was aimed to encourage women turned into a controversial topic that made people change the way they think and view certain things. That is an immensely powerful thing, and it can occur because of the power of the internet. But at the same time, it can be extremely dangerous. In recent times, the high-risk political hacks and the eye-catching news headlines about hacker groups have died down, mainly because governments have been able to crack down on perpetrators and put them away but it is still not completely dead. Nowadays, we do not necessarily need for hacker groups to expose a video or something we can do it our selves using social media platforms. It has almost become the battlefield where wars are to be fought but instead of the gunfights and killing, you can sit in your home and if need be anonymously help create change across the globe, we are seeing it everywhere now for example with the “Black Lives Matter” where people would come together online and shed light on important social topics and try to hold a peaceful protest in support of that cause. This concept sounds like it should work, but what happens is there are other groups of people who instead look to use this movement as a reason cause social chaos. People end up using this newfound internet power for selfish reasons and this causes doubt for when a serious matter occurs. False accusations are an example of how dangerous the internet can be, someone who holds a resentment for someone else can accuse them of something horrible and manipulate other people in hopes of them rallying behind that false accusation. We see it a lot nowadays that if someone is accused of something most likely they are going to lose their careers and reputation before anything is even proven. Because of the general knowledge of how common it is for a women to be harassed and any accusation that comes forth is taken very seriously and rightfully so because if I were to guess 98% of the time the accusations are true but we must not dismiss the other 2% when the other person made the situation up or exaggerating on the events that happened. Unfortunately, by the time an accusation is deemed false the damage has already been done to the accused’s life. In conclusion, this brings up the question of how fast we should embrace what people say online, knowing how effective our stance can be is very important to acknowledge and that some people might try exploit that fact for personal gains but we can not just ignore matters that can potentially be important. So, critical thinking and research is a must.

On the night of August 11th, 2012 In the sleepy rustbelt town of Steubenville, Ohio, a teen sexual assault case made national headlines when two members of the football team of the local high school (Ma’lik Richmond and Trent Mays who were both 16 at the time of the attack) sexually assaulted a girl at a party while she was intoxicated.. After this incident, notorious shadowy vigilante hacktivist group known as “Anonymous” caught wind of the story and decided that they are going to handle the situation themselves. Anonymous got their hands on videos, images, and social media from the night of the sexual assaults and posted them to their millions of followers on various platforms. These social media posts soon caught a lot of attention and went viral, subsequently, the hashtag #JusticeForJaneDoe began trending. Following this online campaign regarding the assaults, people became very passionate about this issue and many people on the internet campaigned to have these two students “cancelled” and their lives to this day are now effectively ruined for their actions. The videos, images and social media that was revealed by anonymous exposed the borderline apathetic attitude that the assailants had. During the court hearing, Ma’lik collapsed in his lawyers arms, complaining about how is life is over. The disgusting acts that these high school football players committed to this girl are in my opinion, atrocious. Trent Mays attempted to cover up the entire incident by telling his friends to “Just say she came to your house and passed out.” As well as trying to convince the victim not to move forward with pressing charges against them. In an Instagram post put up by a fellow football player by the name of Colby Saltsman, the post showed the victim completely unresponsive and being carried by the wrists and ankles by the group of boys. According to the victim she had no memory of the incident and woke up the next morning nude in a room with the football players, missing most of her belongings as well. On March 17th, 2013, Trent Mays and Ma’lik Richmond were convicted for the rape charges, and the judge determined that the victim was intoxicated and could not have possibly given the boys her consent to the actions that took place on that night. Following the charges to the football players, further charges were pressed against school faculty and coaches of the team that knew what those boys had done and they had completely failed to report this to the authorities, or do anything to help the victim at all. Despite video evidence proving the victim was completely unconscious and could not even put a thought together, some people in her local community and on the internet blamed the victim herself for being the one who got raped, and felt that she had brought unnecessary negative attention to not only the town but the football team, and the players who were considered to be star players and very popular among students and staff. The video linked in the assignment poses the following question: “When it seems like nothing will change, when is it OK for outsiders to intervene?” In my opinion, I think in cases such as this that are so reprehensible and intense, no matter how it seems in regards to whether or not things will change, it is OK for outsiders to intervene. I think Anonymous’s actions in lighting the spark to a massive internet campaign that went viral likely was a major factor to the victim of the case getting the verdict she desired, especially given the unfortunate status quo at the time in 2012 regarding rape culture, where it was somewhat commonplace for the victim to not be trusted. I believe that this intervention from the group Anonymous was also a distinct factor in the #MeToo movement in the years that followed, and the ever brighter spotlight on rape culture in the United States, helping to bring the conversation about this harsh topic to the national scale, and normalizing the ability for women to come forward and share their stories, and attempt to move past the trauma that these events have caused them. Following the sentencing, it was determined that whether or not Ma’lik Richmond and Trent Mays will be added to the sex offender registry depends on a further hearing when they are both 21 to judge their behavior at the time and whether or not they have changed. Ma’lik Richmond was released from his detention on January 5, 2014 and Trent Mays was released the following year in January of 2015. If Anonymous had not intervened in the manner that they did, this case likely never would have caught such a viral wave and grab the attention of the country in the manner that it did, and without that who knows if the girl would have gotten the verdict that she deserved for the actions that took place on the night of the incident. On top of this, this was foreshadowing the #MeToo movement that would dominate social media just a few years later. In the aftermath of the incident, it was covered and depicted multiple times in pop culture including the play “Good Kids” by Naomi Lizuka, and even the teen drama series “Degrassi” had a two episode arc based on the events in its thirteenth season. Ana Golja played the victim and the depiction appears in the episodes “unbelievable” and “believe”. The 2014 Lifetime channel movie “The Assault” is also loosely based on the events that took place in the Stuebenville, Ohio incident. In conclusion, I think that in a case like this, regarding outside intervention, in my opinion the ends do justify the means. I don’t think Anonymous crossed any moral boundaries at all by rightfully exposing Ma’lik Richmond and Trent Mays for the horrible acts that they put the victim through. Without Anonymous stepping in in a vigilante like manner to handle the situation on their own in their own way by blowing the incident up on social media, I personally don’t know how likely it is that the victim would have gotten the verdict that she deserved in this case. After the incident blew up on social media I feel like the spotlight that all of the attention shined on the toxic rape culture in the United States was important for planting the seeds of the coming #MeToo movement and both normalizing and allowing for women to speak openly and more comfortably than they had been able to in the past regarding exposing their abusers and or rapists. I think that ultimately, when it comes to things like this when you don’t have faith in the law or the courts, it is okay to act outside of the law and seek justice on your own and in your own way.

On August 12, 2012, in Steubenville, Ohio, a 16-year-old girl was sexually assaulted at a party by two members of the Steubenville football team, Big Red. The two perpetrators of the rape, Ma’lik Richmond and Trent Mays, were rising stars in the town’s high school sporting scene, as well as Ohio state sports at large. Mays was a quarterback in the Big Red football team, and Richmond was a quick and tall wide receiver, as well as a star of the basketball and track teams. Months after the rape, on December 24, 2012, the website of the Steubenville football team, rollredroll.com, was revealed to have been hacked by online hacker identity Anonymous. Then, on January 2, Anonymous released a leaked video taken by students the night of the rape, depicting an adolescent named Michael Nodianos laughing and making jokes about the abused girl. This video quickly gathered many views and was spread virally through social media. After seeing the video, many people began making social media posts tagging news agencies, demanding coverage of the events. Thus, Anonymous’ actions are responsible for national media attention on Steubenville and the perpetrators of the rape. This media attention brought to light the crimes committed by Mays and Richmond, likely further than they would have been investigated without Anonymous’ actions. It also placed Steubenville in the midst of a much larger societal audience than it had been accustomed to. In this essay, I will examine Anonymous’ intervention into the case, and its ethical merit. To begin my analysis into the ethics involved in Anonymous’ intervention in the Steubenville rape case, I will examine it from a series of ethical frameworks. The social contexts involved are so diverse, that there is not a single way to objectively determine the ethical value of Anonymous’ actions. The first perspective I will examine is that of a citizen of Steubenville. This will be someone who is well immersed in the town’s sentiment, news, and customs; someone whose identity is entangled with the town, but uninvolved in the crime itself. The next perspective I will examine is that of one of the hackers, deliberately invested in infiltrating and disrupting the town’s response to the rape of Jane Doe. Steubenville is a small city of around 18,400 people. Right now, it lies in the wake of a massive loss in population, beginning in the mid-1900s. Once a bustling environment with many jobs to offer in the steel and coal industries, the city now faces an outflow of residents, and an inflow of crime. Now, Steubenville’s main claim to fame is its football team, Big Red. The town’s official website claims that Big Red is “keeping Steubenville on the map.” Thus, the townspeople are strongly invested in the town’s high school sporting events, to the point where Big Red is the town’s main source of a sense of importance. One resident, Jim Flanagan, says: “People live and die based on Big Red because they usually win and it makes everybody feel good about themselves when times are tough.” Flanagan also mentions that “the [Big Red] players are considered heroes, and … they’ve been able to get away with things for years because of it … Everyone just looks the other way.” The residents of Steubenville had a history of brushing to the side uncomfortable topics like rape, especially when it was regarding their football team. In Nancy Schwartzman’s video for The Guardian, a Steubenville resident named Geri says: “It is hard to actually even get anybody in this area to discuss rape. And if they do, it’s kind of a little bit, and then it’s like ‘OK, I’ve had enough, put the subject away, let’s go onto something else.’” The townspeople of Steubenville had a tendency to look the other way and blame the victim, especially due to the cognitive dissonance of holding their football team so importantly. Indeed, several law enforcement personnel and school faculty made statements indicating sympathy for Mays and Richmond, as if to justify their behavior. At the same time, Schwartzman’s video showcases Steubenville town members expressing anger and resentment about the way Anonymous’ actions painted their town. Many felt that the video leaks and resulting media spotlight painted Steubenville in a harsh light, with negative consequences for the vast majority of townsfolk uninvolved in the crime. In one section of the video, Steubenville citizens rally together in response to the pressure from the media and external world, speaking about how people following the story “want [Steubenville citizens] to be ashamed to wear red and black … to be ashamed of [their] tradition.” One speaker says “this case is in the legal system … let them handle it!” The dissatisfaction of these people is justified. Onlookers following the story through Twitter and news reports see Steubenville only as the town in which a horrific rape occurred and was recorded and laughed at. To Steubenville’s citizens, however, the town is their entire lives. I can understand the townspeople’s frustration at their town’s portrayal in the media, associating its name with a heinous crime committed by only two of its residents. On the other hand, it was explicitly stated by a resident of Steubenville that its townspeople had an unwillingness to discuss rape. It’s hard to distinguish the townspeople’s frustration from a desire to simply make the bad press go away, and get on with things the way they used to be. Due to the viral attention garnered by the video leaked by Anonymous, it’s clear that their actions had a direct effect on the sentencing of Mays and Richmond, who were charged with rape in March of the following year. Considering the town’s psychological dependence on the football team for a sense of relevance, it’s likely that Mays and Richmond would not have faced adequate consequences for their actions, especially since they were skilled players who were leading Big Red in its sporting matches. Anonymous even claimed that the coach of the football team aided Mays in covering up the rape. On the other hand, the hackers who investigated and exposed the crime, as well as media outlets reporting on it, were unfamiliar with the subtleties of the town’s social dynamics. Since Steubenville’s football team was its main source of attention, by directly attacking the merit of that team, the media indirectly attacked the sense of identity of the townsfolk. It’s hard to gauge the intentions of Anonymous members. While some were undoubtedly motivated by a sense of justice, it’s easy to imagine an alluring sense of drama surrounding the case, which sees the town only in light of the crime, discarding everything else it has to offer. All things considered, Anonymous’ actions were more ethically justified than unjustified, and produced more positive change in Steubenville than negative. It’s true that the mass media attention to the town may have had an immediate negative effect on many citizens who were uninvolved in the crime, but that’s only because they were complicit in unhealthy patterns of behavior rampant in the town: patterns of covering up rape and crime, particularly when it related to the football team. Anonymous’ actions, and the subsequent results, seeded new possibilities for the town and how victims of sexual assault were able to speak out about their abuse.

In a video published by The Guardian, we are told the story of a town changed by Anonymous. Steubenville, Ohio, was a small and quiet town that was best known for their high school sports and for the most part went under the radar. In 2012, hacker group Anonymous got wind of a story about two members of the town’s high school football team committing sexual assault. This would lead to the rewriting of Steubenville’s identity as a town as well as sparking a global viral movement. Anonymous was created in 2003 on an imageboard website called 4chan as a concept of many members of a community existing together as a digital information network. This online community initially acted in protests, pranks, and hacks in an anonymous but coordinated manner. Anonymous went on to grow and gain worldwide recognition for its large-scale cyber-attacks on governments and corporations. The Steubenville high school rape case was one of such attacks. Under Anonymous’ op roll red roll, #JusticeforJaneDoe became the motto of viral outrage as Anonymous began raising awareness of the assault. As evidence of the assault grew, so did the demands. The small town of Steubenville was divided and became a center of passionate mobs seeking retribution. At the same time, generations of women who hid abuse were stirred and emboldened. While they may not have fought for their own justice, they fought ferociously for their fellow woman. “This film asks, when it seems like nothing will change, when is it OK for outsiders to intervene?” This is the grounds of several ethical dilemma’s that I will address. Going in chronological order, the first thing to question would be Anonymous’ initial decision to intervene. First, those in favor of intervention at this stage would say that the justice system is not doing its job well enough here. This case was not dealt with adequately, and justice was not served. Further action must be made to spark a change in the way that the system currently runs. I agree with this sentiment because the high school football members would have gotten away with the sexual assault without the intervention. Those against the intervention may say that it is not the responsibility of the hacker group to be the actors here. Perhaps it should be the victim or her friends or family to speak up. Perhaps it should be the criminals who should speak up out of guilt. However, these are weak arguments in my opinion and are not strong enough grounds for ethical analysis. It can not be expected that someone else will take action for your cause and taking appropriate action is generally the better move than assuming someone else will take responsibility. The next stage would be to examine the aspects of escalation that Anonymous used. This is where most of the ethical analysis will be done as it addresses a social dilemma – national attention. By publicizing social media and particularly the Nodi video, one in favor of the intervention could argue that in order to further the cause, evidence should be used and perhaps so should anything that could help strengthen your position. In its own way, simply putting information out there can give you the impression that you are a superhero. This aspect of social engineering was used quite effectively at this stage. On the other hand, this evidence was very specifically incriminating. Tweets, comments, videos, etc. exposing specific people at a national level always comes with a host of problems. This could all too easily fall into doxing territory and lead to an overcompensation on the side of punishment and far outweighing a just penalty. If we were to talk about this from a justice perspective, even the victim’s name was publicized, which is not just at all. This outroar clearly overstepped its original intent and turned into something else at this point. The student behind the Nodi video was no doubt penalized because of Anonymous’ intervention too – it can be inferred that his college career had been impacted as he was no longer enrolled at his college after the uproar. (while his reaction was atrociously disgusting, stupidity is not a criminal offense) To extend this stance, the clamor about this case was unfair to the town as a whole. The New York Times gave a very detailed account of the circumstances around the assault and the events that unfolded behind it bringing a negative spotlight on a town that had previously not been given much coverage. To those who are invested in the town, this is terrible news. They would like to move past it and move on and don’t deserve the labelling from all the media and publicity. The nature of viral outrage is very unforgiving, and this town was labeled and identified on an arguably undeserved scale for the assault case. There is no doubt that similar cases and worse have happened and still happen all around the world today, but this town happened to be the one to take the blame. Anonymous’ intervention in this light was unfortunate. And then, of course, the testimonies started coming out. As a result of all this online attention, we were able to witness a tirade transform and give birth to a worldwide movement of empowerment and social justice. As this viral outrage turned into a viral message, it came with a shift in societal and ethical implications. To analyze Anonymous’ intervention at this stage is akin to taking a stance on whether or not the ends justify the means. Those in favor would say that retrospectively, this was a net positive. The way that things played out benefited the world and turned out for the better. Thanks to Anonymous, multiple generations of women were able to come out and share their story. Millions of people were in solidarity with each other and supported and encouraged each other. Sexual assault, which was slightly taboo, was brought to light and addressed on a legal scale but perhaps more importantly on a huge social scale. Sexual harassment protections have gone up, everywhere from Hollywood to the Olympics have been put under the spotlight for sexual harassment, and public perception of the prevalence of misconduct in America has been shifted. Those against the intervention at this stage would say that Steubenville and the criminals paid too great a price for this to be called “justice.” It can be said that we cannot measure one’s suffering up against another’s or even many others. However, once again I believe this argument lacks substance in the scheme of all of society as I am somewhat utilitarian in this scenario. So there we have my analysis of ethical aspects on when it is okay to intervene as an outsider when it seems like nothing will change broken down in chronological order as it played out in the Steubenville high school rape case. In conclusion, the initial intervention was justified, the viral outroar was vastly over tuned, and yet, society at large seems to be left for the better as a result. Sometimes phenomena like these are required for us to change.

On August 11, 2012, a 16-year-old girl, Jane Doe in Steubenville who got drunk and raped by two high school football stars when she went to a party with friends, and the two football players not just took advantage on her, but also toyed, humiliated and took nude photo of her. Few days after the party, her naked picture was circulated among the classmates. One of the rapists even joked around in social media said that, “If they’re getting ‘raped’ and don’t resist then to me it’s not rape. I feel bad for her but still.”[1] After such social media posts posted, Doe’s family reported the alleged assault to the police. And the police quickly identify those two suspects: Trent Mays and Ma’lik Richmond. Since all the evidence like tweets, Instagram posts and text messages sent between Doe and the boys restored the whole story with timeline, both of them got arrested a week later. But then the most horrendous part came in, the Steubenville community, which was once best known for high school sports decided to protect the rapists instead of the victim because these two young men had a bright futures as a football star and the girl was just nobody, the locals don’t even see rape as a crime. When the Steubenville community trying to cover up the rape case, the Anonymous kicked in and reveal the truth. Their goal is to gain more attention of higher authorities in this case. They hacked into the Steubenville booster club website, RollRedRoll.com and the videos went viral in social media. Millions of their followers stand up and demands justice for Doe. They gathered in the small town to give pressures to the local authorities and provided support and strength to the girl.[2] When I watched the documentary for the first time, the way that the people in the town who still trying to cover up the story and upsetting that such negative attentions were brought to their town disgust me the most. They are afraid to discuss rape and assume that “things can get out of hand” is acceptable when girls and boys were getting drunk. The worst part is this is not the first case that happened in the town: victims got blamed for seeking help, police department can choose if they want to take the case or not and victims need to learn how to protect themselves. It is hard to imagine how helpless and frustrated Doe would feel if the Anonymous did not expose the truth. After the case getting international attention, both Mays and Richmond were found guilty at the end. In 2017, one of the Anonymous hackers was sentenced two years in prison for conspiring to illegally access a computer without authorization and lying to an FBI agent. [3] While the rapists were received to one year and two-year sentence. This rape case brings out the ethical side of hackers. As we known, there are three types of hacker, the white hat, black hat, and grey hat. The white hat hacker can be seen as a good hacker who hack ethically and used their knowledge to test the system under permission, usually are paid employees or security company. Black hat hacker doing malicious hacking such as writing malware to break into networks and gain access to the systems. Their main motivation is usually for money or just simply addicted in committing cybercrime. The most complication one, is the grey hacker. They wander around the grey area and do what both black hat and white hat did, but most of the time, they are not malicious yet not always ethical as well. [4] In recent years, there emerged some other hat colors like blue, green and red hat hacker which represent different hacking skills and motivations. In this case, Anonymous was in a gray hat hacker position. In the point of view of the Steubenville community, Anonymous was the one to blame for ruining their town’s reputation, but the victim and other possible victims see them as a savior that do just for them and encourage them to speak out for themselves. If wasn’t them, no one will reveal the truth and the truth will be covered forever, and all the victims can do is just suffer and hide their wounds. But for those who committed crime will go free and might continue to harm others. Like the Steubenville town’s people, claimed that they are church people and not bad people, choose to turn a blind eye on the crime that done in front of them, they care more about their image and reputation than someone getting raped. While for the police department, they will think that Anonymous are provoking the right of authorities and trying to serve justice on their own. But rationally speaking, the way they acted might not be ethical (hacking into people’s private system) but if they do it for good intention and does not harm others, they deserved a lighter penalty. I understand that if they don’t receive any kind of punishment, this will encourage people to be a hacker and do justice on their own, but in the moral side, what they do is acceptable and they did it because the incapable of the justice system. Recently the Anonymous was coming back to serve for George Floyd case by making announcement that addressed Floyd’s killing and the larger pattern of police misconduct, concluding, “We will be exposing your many crimes to the world. We are legion. Expect us.”.[5] The comments below it were mostly welcome and excited for their comeback. This makes me think of the powerless of current law enforcement agencies and justice system, that made public trusted a group of hackers instead of the law and government.

A hacker group called Anonymous claims that a party took place in the town of Steubenville, Ohio. They claimed that a group of football players that went to Big Red high school took advantage of an underage girl. That girl was sexually assaulted, raped, and dragged unconsciously from party to party. The students were aware of this action; however, they had kept quiet to keep the football team a star. One of the students wanted to help and spread out the information and they were able to as soon as Anonymous threatens to reveal personal information about the football players that were involved in the incident. Other online users were more confident in spreading out this information on Twitter, group conversations, and private messages. Due to this, they set up a rally in the town for the voices to be heard. One of the speakers articulated that if the Anonymous group hadn’t brought national attention to the rape case, then it would have disappeared like many of the other rape cases. This process gave strength to generations of women, survivors, who were forced to have hidden their abuse to start speaking up about their personal experiences with rape with confidence and courage. Although this rally was successful, there were still a few townspeople who did not appreciate it because of the negative publicity. They had created havoc and parents were concerned about their children being ashamed of the school that they were going to. They wanted the legal system to handle the case and wanted the media to stop the story so they can move on past it. Eventually, two Steubenville high school football players were founded guilty of sexual assault and served up to two years in a juvenile detention center. When it seems like nothing will change, when is it OK for outsiders to intervene? I believe that it was okay for Anonymous to have to intervene in a case like this because this was a serious case that many of the townspeople just let slide. The ethical aspect of the situation I would say is consequentialism because it focuses on the consequences of the actions. An act is morally right if and only if that act causes the greatest happiness for the greatest number. Having an outsider intervene is called humanitarian intervention. “Humanitarian intervention is justified because the international community has a moral duty to protect common humanity and because there is a legal obligation, codified in international law, for states to intervene against large human rights abuses” (Matthewman). If it had not been for the hacker group Anonymous, the rape case that happened in Big Red high school would have ignored by everyone and that girl would not have been able to have gotten her justice. It is okay for a third party to intervene if it seems like nothing will change because that third party can help make a change and make voices heard. It is ethical because it is a moral duty to protect civilians from human rights abuses. “The right to life is an essential concept of natural law, and it provides the foundation of the justification for humanitarian intervention because the right to life is a universally accepted norm” (Mathewman). Going back to consequentialism, this action brings about more benefits than harm and that is a good thing. This aligns with the act of utilitarianism because these ethics produce more pleasure causing outcomes than pain-causing ones. Matthewman, Joshua. “Humanitarian Intervention: An Exploration of Its Justification and Best Practices.” E, 13 Feb. 2012, . Phillips, Charlie, and Jacqueline Edenbrow. “Anonymous Comes to Town: the Hackers Who Took on High School Sexual Assault in Ohio – Documentary.” The Guardian, Guardian News and Media, .

The concept of hacktivism has become a long and controversial subject matter in today’s society, especially due to people’s perception on whether the concept is right or wrong. The infamous hacking group, otherwise known as Anonymous, utilizes the concept of hacktivism to bring awareness and apprehension towards real-life occurring social issues. They demonstrate the usage of hacktivism with a well-known sexual assault case that caused uproar in the small town of Steubenville, located in Ohio. This case caused a national outrage as Anonymous released a video that assisted in creating a case. Now, the argument manifests to be: when is it ok for outsiders, such as Anonymous, to intervene? The definition of hacktivism can be very contentious, but it is most commonly known as “a form of non-violent digital activism where the motive is not, primarily, personal financial gain. Instead, hacktivist campaigns aim to achieve political, social, or religious justice in line with the group’s cause. Hackers use tactics such as doxing, defacement, and denial-of-service to break into government or private organization [1]”. Anonymous proves that the use of hacktivism can be justified, especially with a serious case such as rape. With doxing, they are able to leak personal information that maybe confidential or incriminating against organizations or public figures, in this case, it is against two high school football players who sexually assaulted an underaged girl. The group Anonymous was able to obtain access of the video in which the sexual assault took place and released it on the internet. This video eventually caused anger and rage across Steubenville as it divided the town. Many actually argued against Anonymous and what they were doing because they viewed the issue as an invasion of privacy. Others argued that the action of releasing the video shun upon a light on the issue of rape and sexual assault, especially for women who were not heard when they spoke out. “The idea that a rape victim made up her story is still floating around, despite photos of the girl being carried around while allegedly unconscious by her alleged attackers [2]”. This exemplifies how divided the town became as everyone had a different perception on what really happened on the night of the assault. The police chief for Steubenville even begged for witnesses to come forward, but unfortunately, received very little responses. Once the testimony was released, it was said that the case resulted in becoming a “women’s movement” as it encouraged women to speak out against past and current sexual assaults. In the film [3], a woman named Alesha, a citizen of Steubenville spoke out and stated, “she was raped in 2000, reported it to the police, they called me saying that they couldn’t do anything for me.” Many of these sexual assault survivors that spoke out did not receive justice in any way. This further emphasizes when its ok for outsiders, in this case being Anonymous, to intervene. “Hacktivists carry out data breaches for more than monetary gain. Instead, their distinct agenda wages an informational war for political lean, social justice, religious intent, or anarchy [1]”. In this instance, Anonymous did not release the video for money, fame or notoriety, instead they utilized the video to call for social justice in the case of the 16-year-old girl who was seen being violated and assaulted by two high school football players in the controversial video. The controversy behind the case goes even to the extent of one of Steubenville High’s 19 football coaches to say “The rape was just an excuse, I think … What else are you going to tell your parents when you come home drunk like that and after a night like that? She had to make up something. Now people are trying to blow up our football program because of it [2]”. It was necessary for Anonymous to intervene and clarify the truth of what happened that night, this was proven with the quick grasp of national attention. Many would argue that the act of releasing the video sparked a positive movement for social change along the topic of sexual assault. This emotional case was stamped as a reference for when people need to speak out. Ethically, the actions of Anonymous may have been a violation of privacy, but the outcome and results were bigger than the action itself. It helped bring justice to the girl, who was recognized by the public as Jane Doe, and it also assisted in bringing back past rape charges and allegations that were ignored. Geri, a resident of Steubenville for forty years and a participant in the film [3], gave her story on how she was ignored by the police when she was sexually assaulted. She states, “I was sexually assaulted. When I called the sheriff’s office I said, ‘I want to see if I can prosecute.’ The response that I got from the deputy that I spoke to was, ‘Oh, I know him, and the prosecutor has decided that he is not going to take the case.’” This shows how women are overlooked, certainly for cases and allegations that were related to rape. Anonymous helped these “overlooked” women tell their story. This made it even more obvious as to why Anonymous intervened, considering that police ignored previous allegations. The national controversy on this case expanded the conversation on whether hacktivism was good or bad. Society did not know what to label Anonymous as, considering that they’re a “hacking group” and people did not know whether their intentions or work was for positive or negative use. According to the article [4], there are different kinds of hackers with good intentions. “Those hackers who aren’t simply launching malicious cyberattacks for personal gain are referred to as white hat hackers, ethical hackers, or hacktivists. They can actually play an important role in society, as protectors of the public good, ensuring governments and companies don’t abuse their power.” Overall, Anonymous intervened with the intent of exposing the high school football players and to gain justice for the girl who was assaulted. The video, which served as proof and eventually caused for a case, escalated and caught the attention of people all over the nation. The action of providing the video to the public was a perfect example of when its ok for the public to intervene.

Ethical issues related to technology related to the privacy, security, risks, and safety issues brought about by the use of technology [1]. The use of technology comes with a number of challenges and professionals in the field have the ethical responsibility to protect not only the customers but the society as a whole. With a sensitivity of the information in society, it is important for technology users to consider the impact of their actions on society. Understanding the various stakeholders is key in knowing the ethical problems relating to them. When it comes to sensitive information users should list all the possible causes of action and the list of consequences for the chosen cause of action. The consequences in this case include the beneficiaries and benefits as well as the risks [2]. The impact on stakeholders, in this case, should relate to the risks, consequences, costs, and harm. The options taken by the decision-maker should be considered to be ethical and in this case the prohibitions, obligations, and acceptance [3]. Choosing an option, one should choose one based on courtesy to other, ethical merits, practicability, self-interest, and personal preferences. Anonymous is one famous group using the internet to protest against a series of societal problems. The case of the anonymous is a classic case of ethical issues related to the use and application of technology. Anonymous posted a rape tape involving the Steubenville high school girl raped by a football team [4]. The group demanded justice for Jane Doe who was raped by the team members and the entire town was divided over the issue. Ethical Implications of the Leaked Tape Benefits from Anonymous Rape Leak There are several benefits and costs associated with the information leaked by anonymous concerning the rape case. The information released came with costs, benefits, and risks in the small silent town of Steubenville. The benefits that came with the leaked information pertaining to the strength given to the women who opened up on rape cases they held dearly. Several women opened up on how the silent town was covering heinous crimes and atrocities committed by the inhabitants of the small town. The women were able to open up on the abuses they have faced and how society has forced them to hide their pain [2]. The post, therefore, proved in the small town that it was very ok for outsiders to intervene in the situation. Justice for Jane Doe was served plainly because the entire post by anonymous gave the world a clear picture of what exactly was happening. The school girl’s ordeal could have been covered up just like the many rape cases the small town had managed to cover-up. Being the Big Red players probably gave the players a false sense of security as they were protected by their parents as well as their teachers. In a field where evidence is always hard to find and go-by, the post by the anonymous [1]. With police always finding it hard to find evidence relating to such personal crimes, the post was incriminating for the football players. Despite the fact that some of the rapists were not prosecuted in the case involving the rape, the prosecution of the two found on tape served the school. With threats to the girl’s family for her coming forward and the lack of evidence since the girl took a shower [3]. The technology was very beneficial therefore to the girl who was served justice for rape and the women who gained the courage and served the right platform to open up on rape. The other benefit from the technology derived from this case is the prevention of crime and individuals are more afraid of committing such atrocities. Technology has been applied in solving cases where the evidence could be sufficient for the prosecution like this case where DNA could not be available [1]. This makes technology beneficial to the current society. Costs Associated Anonymous Girls Public Image In crimes involving rape and other serious identity crimes, the victims have always been kept anonymous to the world. Such trials happen in closed courts with no videos to protect the identity of the victims as well as their families. In the case involving the Big Red footballers, the identity of the victim became public as one of the witnesses kept mentioning the name of the girl [2]. The stigma associated with such mention makes the victim vulnerable and in some cases, victims end up committing suicide. The families of such victims face a lot of problems handling authorities and parties who always want such cases dropped. The victim in the rape involving the Big Red was victimized after the rape with fellow students referring to her as a slut [2]. This s the most traumatizing aspect of rape apart from titillates and embarrassment brought by rape. Costs to the Society The small town of Steubenville came to the public limelight for all the wrong reasons after the rape accusations involving the Big Red. The city’s image was tarnished and the hidden crimes that have been committed came to the limelight. The reputation of the entire city was lost in a case that could be solved more amicably. The interests of anonymous in this case were selfish. By posting such information the identities of the third parties to the case could no longer be hidden. The school’s reputation can never be revived and some of the employees lost their jobs and sources of livelihoods [4]. The rape perpetrators have their images damaged for the rest of their lives. Despite serving the sentence there criminal records will always include the rape allegation. With such a publicized case the two men will have to live with the trauma associated with their action. The damage to the societal image was even made worse by the fact that other victims came out to explain their experience in the city with rapists [1]. It means therefore that if anonymous had considered the implications of the information the damage to the victim, society, and the perpetrator could not be that much. If the cases had been solved by contacting only the authorities the small city could not lose its reputation. It is however important to note some cases have failed due to authorities refusing to follow up on crimes like rape. The move by anonymous could have been spiked by such unsolved cases. Conclusion Technology remains the greatest invention in the history of the man bringing with it a number of blessings and curses. It has created the easiest way to communicate and enabled individuals to interact more easily in society. Several cases have been highlighted globally all thanks to technology [4]. Some of the most heinous crimes like rape cases have been solved thanks to technology even in cases when DNA samples were missing. The same technology has also created a negative impact on society. More and more individuals are having their private lives brought to the limelight. Individuals using the technology should however be more careful with how they use it. Weighing the benefits and the costs will prevent the negative effects of technology on society [4]. The rightful use of technology is preventing more crimes that could be occurring in society. More and more criminal cases are being solved through the use of technology. Understanding technology including the benefits and shortfalls will make society a better place.

Not many people know about the town of Steubenville known for their Dean Martin attractions. This all changed when news that a sexual assault case had occured involving none other than the shining stars of the Big Red football team. This case was huge, especially for a small town such as Steubenville, and it did not get much better after the hacker group known as Anonymous started contributing in their own way. Unsurprisingly they sided with the victim, threatening the players and exposing a private video of the night of the assault for everyone to see. This inevitably changed the course of Steubenville’s future and this will be analyzed in the perspective of a Utilitarian and a Deontologist in order to determine whether or not Anonymous was ethically right in making their decision. Through the lens of Utilitarianism, the act committed by the group known as Anonymous would be justified because it benefits the greater good. By hacking the school football website and publicly posting the video of what happened at the night of the assault, Anonymous drew attention to the situation and started a chain reaction of events leading up to a decisive court case. People started commenting not only online, but also outside in the streets as well. This is first shown when Anonymous organizes a gathering in order to protest the injustice and spur a legal case. Starting this movement gave people a chance to speak up on similar experiences and voice their stories so that everyone could be aware of the broken justice system in their own police department. This eventually led to increased overall “happiness” in Steubenville because as more sexual assault cases are being brought to light, citizens begin to feel more reassured about the safety of their own people. In addition, this case was broadcasted throughout the entire country and possibly even further so that goes to show the reach of what Anonymous did and how many more people the case is affecting in a positive way, besides Steubenville. The group’s actions could inspire other victims from all over to speak up like it did with Steubenville and help cleanse society of rapists. Although there was some unhappiness caused by the disturbing video, such as the attackers of the victim and their families, the happiness generated from the victims and the rest of the community outweighs those negatives. Bob Fitzsimmons, the attorney for the sexual assault victim, states “--she’s really happy this is over” and how it is a “big relief” for her and her family that the case ended the way that it did [1]. Therefore, in this way, Anonymous has achieved the greatest happiness for the greatest number of people by exposing the football players and other hidden stories of sexual assault. Others, however, may not agree with the Utilitarian perspective and argue that the actions of Anonymous were more harmful than not. Before Anonymous intervened, the town of Steubenville was a quiet one in which most of the action revolved around their high school football team. A local from the area even says, “Everybody around here goes to games on Friday nights” [2]. Due to the significance of the football team, when players were accused of sexually assaulting a drunk girl some might have even tried to look the other way because they do not want to endanger the only thing great about Steubenville. Of course this was met with the fact that others believed that, no matter what, they should be held accountable. These differences in opinions eventually split up the small town and left it abandoned and unemployed. The New York Times described Steubenville as a “graveyard” and police say it has had a major increase in drug problems [2]. Although Anonymous may have had the right mindset going forward with exposing the football players, it definitely was not for the greater good of Steubenville -- a town divided due to the acts of Anonymous. A deontologist’s point of view would have to agree with the argument that Anonymous did not make the right ethical decision in this case. The act of hacking into a website and exposing private information -- the video -- would not be morally justified even if that meant the assaulters would never have been caught. The fact that the two football players sexually assaulted the girl is also unethical as deontology would never allow that. However, this ethical ideal does not account for the consequences of an action but judges based on whether or not that action individually is moral. Thus, due to Anonymous imposing on the privacy of the football players and the assault victim, they would be morally wrong to have exposed and divided the town of Steubenville in such a manner. Instead, the group, Anonymous, should have left the situation to the police in order for the crime to be processed in a more organized fashion. Although, as mentioned before, the citizens of Steubenville love their football team very much and many are known to look the other way even when they know the players are involved in something shady. William McCafferty, the chief of police in Steubenville, states “if crimes are being committed, -- they aren’t being reported”[2]. In addition, the ends did not justify the means because Steubenville was in a state of shambles after the two players were found guilty and Anonymous destroyed the only thing that has kept the town going for years. The destruction of the town as a consequence of Anonymous’ action further proves the point that they made the wrong decision and it was not for the greater good of Steubenville. Ultimately, there are pros and cons and evidence to support both Utilitarianism and Deontology but at the end of it all it seems clear that Anonymous should not have intervened in this matter. The consequence of their intervention caused the entire town of Steubenville to suffer major losses as a society without any big-picture benefits. In other words, the fact that the group Anonymous aided in inspiring others to not shy away from their own tragedies ended up not doing much in terms of amounting to the “greater good” and actually made Steubenville worse off. There may have been no correlation with this case inspiring people other than the Steubenville residents and therefore it is not enough to justify the actions of Anonymous. Anonymous left the town torn apart just to impose on a case that did not have anything to do with them and did not think twice.

Hacktivism is a form of non-violent digital activism where the motive is not primarily for​ personal gain.As many people around the world know Hacktivism is a very important version of activision because it helps people in need create a voice that was silenced to begin with. In the situation, a underage girl from a small town called Steubenville in Ohio ​ was raped by members​ of their major football team, after the police were notified the football players were still never prosecuted, this led to an uproar of emotions and it created national attention.What made this situation even more appalling was the fact that these boys filmed themselves making fun of this serious situation by recording and taking pictures of this traumatizing situation in this girls life. After this video had been posted publicly the hacktivist group known as Anonymous had received information regarding this act of injustice and publicly made it known they were coming for them if justice was not served and it led to these men being held accountable for their actions. Anonymous hacktivism is very closely similar to the ideas of John Rawls and his​ philosophy, John Rawls philosophy was focusing on the treatment of fairness to others and especially others of the less fortunate. In my opinion this is exactly the purpose of Anonymous to bring attention and help people that can't help themselves. Furthermore Without the help of Anonymous this case wouldn’t have got this much attention because it would have been swept under the rug and silenced like most rape cases because women are not protected under this legal system. Hacktivism is also very important for people because it lets people that are suffering know that they are being heard and someone is willing to help. This situation has led to many women speaking out on being raped and sexually assaulted as young women and adults which had sparked viral outrage and demands for #JusticeforJaneDoe. This situation is a prime example of how one situation can start a domino effect that can create change. There are many ways to look into hacktivision but it is quite clear that there are positive rights and negative rights to being a hacktivist. As many know some positive rights would be the ability to help others and let their injustice be heard to many people around the world which could spark a change. On the other hand there are some negative rights to hacktivism because many people won't agree with either the situation or the way the hacktivist are going about the situation which could overshadow the actual problem the hacktivist is trying to shed light on. Another ethical point of view when viewing hacktivism is from the theories of Immanuel Kant which was known for his view on Deontological theories. The definition of a Deontological theory is absolute rules to be followed whether they lead to good or ill consequences in particular cases. Ethically hacktivision leans more towards John Rawls views and his philosophy because it benefits people who need their voice to be heard which would most likely be minorities or women but it can also be interpreted in Immanuel Kant philosophy. Anonymous is willing to go to the full extent to bring down any person, cooperation or government when they see wrong and this is because in most time when they expose these people for their wrong doing it leads to good consequences because it will most likely be the right thing to do but when exposing and creating light on a situation is not guaranteed to go as expected because many people will react the same and others won't. In the present day of 2020 during the times of protest and riots Anonymous posted a video ​ ​ specifically criticizing the Minneapolis police department and ​ explaining its support for​ the activism group black lives matter and that it would be targeting police departments across the United States. As stated in What is Hacktivism? by Panda security​ ​ [1]​ “​ We do not trust your​ corrupted organization to carry out justice, so We will be exposing your many crimes to the​ world”. This act of calling out the injustice of police departments around the country gave a​ national wake up call to many Americans if what police brutality looks like. America saw with their own eyes the many acts of racism black Americans deal with on a day to day basis, once the video was made public of an unarmed black man being murdered in broad daylight it shocked everyone and brought America to a stop and forced police officers to be held accountable for the wrongful killing of George Floyd. Therefore when action took place Anonymous Twitter account exploded in popularity, with an influx of 3.5 million new followers in the days following the video. At the time of writing, the campaign consisted of a series of DDoS attacks that have briefly shut down the Minneapolis police department website, its parent website, and the Buffalo, New York, government site over the course of a weekend. These acts of Hacktivism are very loud and clear, it lets people know that Anonymous is for the people and only the people. The first step of hacktivism Anonymous had claimed to be responsible for in support of black lives matter was taking down the Minneapolis Police Department (MPD) website, breaching a police​ department database, and ​ leaking 798 emails and passwords.​ Anonymous also was responsible​ for convincing Korean pop music fans to hijack pro-police and white supremacist Twitter hashtags in support of Black Lives Matter. K-pop superfans also took down a Dallas police department app for reporting allegedly illegal activity by flooding it with K-pop fan videos[2]. Furthermore it is clear these acts of hacktivism have led to a mostly positive outcome because it gave many people the voice they needed to get more people aware of their situation and or more people involved in order to receive justice. In the case of the small town of Steubenville the act​ of hacktivism led to a positive outcome of uniting a group of people who were completely divided. Once people understood each other and these women stood out to tell their story and how it affected them it displayed an understanding of everyone and why people need to fight against these crimes together. In our society we need to learn to not rely on the justice system because it does nothing to benefit minorities and women therefore we need to stand as a unit to put a end to crimes such as rape and sexual assault.

Anonymous is a hacktivism group whose members prefer to keep themselves...well... anonymous. They started in 2003 on 4chan and first started off with “Project Chanology in 2008—a series of protests, pranks, and hacks targeting the Church of Scientology” [1]. The group has been the leading stars of some very well-known events since then. These events include things like doxing church members who were planning on protesting at the funerals of victims from Sandy Hook Elementary, exposing pedophile websites and their users, targeting ISIS members and so forth. While Anonymous claims to be headless, many people speculate this, and countless members of the group have been arrested. The group in general fights the good fight and has good intentions, although many people who are not a part of the group claim that they are and commit acts not aligned with the groups’ views. I believe in this situation, in a very utilitarian way, that the ends do indeed justify the means. Josh Harkinson highlights this when he says “If this mom comes to you and says, ‘My kid was raped and the police won’t help me and I know who did it,’ what are you supposed to do” [2]. Looking at what Anonymous did in relation to Steubenville from a utilitarianism viewpoint, I believe what they did was ethical. While bringing attention from millions of people to this small town in Ohio did cause a lot of stress to the towns citizens it also brought a lot of positive attention to the MeToo movement. The citizens of this small town were hurt by all the negative media they were receiving at the time, but that time has now passed; internet trolls have moved on with their lives. On the other hand, this event paved the way for so many other women in this town to speak up about their own experiences with sexual assault, it helped them heal. While this did not start the MeToo movement, it definitely gave it a bump in notoriety. It gave women from all over a way to rally with Jane Doe and the other women in this town who experienced similar events themselves. I don’t believe Anonymous planned for this to happen, they just wanted to simply expose the events that transpired and expose those who committed the crimes. Even though they did not bring the attention to this town with the intention to help women all over the world, that’s what it turned into, and for that they are ethically right in what they did. Looking at this situation and evaluating it using deontological ethics could shift the conversation a bit. If the situation is looked at as a whole; rapists form a small town who think they can get away with sexual assault and not face punishment get exposed to millions of people. Personally, I would love it if every person who committed crimes like this were exposed to the internet, there wouldn’t be victim blaming and people would be held accountable for their heinous actions. If the information on these people was already out there and Anonymous republished it that’s one thing, but that’s not what they did. They hacked their way to this information. If everybody tried to hack their way into getting private information off of people because they suspect they have something bad on their phone the world would have no privacy. While people like this should be exposed for their actions, Anonymous is a vigilante group and they are not the law and they could have accidentally posted somebody’s information who wasn’t involved. Publishing private information to the internet that was gained illegally is morally wrong, if everybody did things like this is would be a very harsh world to live in. In this specific situation there are many negative and positive rights at play. Let’s start with Jane Doe and her positive rights. Firstly, Jane Doe, and every woman, has the right to drink and be taken home safely, not be taken advantage of sexually. She also has the right for the police department and other law enforcement agencies to thoroughly investigate, and prosecute any parties involved. One other positive right she has is the right have the guilty party pay for any therapy she needs, whether that be physical or mental. Jane Doe, of course, also has negative rights in this situation. One of her negative rights is the right to freedom, in this case the right to freedom is that she should have been able to leave the second she felt uncomfortable. Another negative right she possesses is the right to safety, she should not have to be afraid of being harmed in any way. She also had the right to privacy by not having her name exposed to the media during an already difficult time, so I am glad Anonymous dubbed her “Jane Doe”. The members of Anonymous also have their own rights. They all have the right to internet since we live in a free country, what they choose to do with that internet access is their own business. Believe it or not, the boys who committed the crime also had positive and negative rights in the situation. After being arrested they had the basic positive rights to an attorney, the right to remain silent and any other rights protecting them in the US judicial system. They also had negative right to privacy, which Anonymous violated. It would be one thing if law enforcement had warrants allowing them to access the information on the boys’ phones, but that’s not what transpired. Overall, the ethics behind hacktivism in general is something that will always be up for debate. This is especially true when a group like Anonymous gets involved and brings the attention of millions of people. In the case of the Steubenville High School students who committed an incredibly heinous crime, the ends justify the hacktivism means. While the students had the right to privacy which was violated by Anonymous, they had violated Jane Doe’s right to safety when they harmed her in a way that will stick with her for the rest of her life. An eye for an eye will make the whole world go blind, but somebody needed to provide justice for a woman when the law enforcement didn’t want to do their job. I believe the outcome of what Anonymous did was worth the ethics they may have violated in the process. That being said, I believe the overall situation was ethical and Anonymous had every right to do what they did.

Hacktivism, also known as Political Hacking, is the use of hacking to promote a political cause. The term is a combination of hack and activism. What makes this different from just regular black hat hacking is that hacktivism is not necessarily done for monetary gain or any outright malicious intent. Instead, it is to expose or express opposition against an injustice that they are seeing and believe more attention needs to be brought to it. Hacktivism is looked at as civil disobedience and low-level information warfare online. Also, it is very similar to political protest, and with the rise of the internet and social media and its importance on everyone's daily lives, not to mention where most people get their information, there can be a rise in hacktivist activities. The situation with the sexual assault in Ohio during August 2012 and how the hacktivist group, Anonymous, shows the impact hacktivism can have on not only an entire city but on its political climate. The video, “Anonymous Comes to Town: The hackers who took on high school sexual assault in Ohio”, is about how some Anonymous members caught wind of a story about a high school girl who was sexually assaulted by some football members and they decided to intervene. The film begs the question, “When it seems like nothing will change, when is it OK for outsiders to intervene?[1]”. The answer to the question does not have a solid concrete answer due to everyone involved, either directly or indirectly, would have a different answer. The Jane doe, the city, the individual citizens, and everyone else. Taking the normative ethics - consequentialism route, we will be looking at the effects of the hacktivism group, Anonymous, actions in this situation. “Consequentialism, as its name suggests, is simply the view that normative properties depend only on consequences. This historically important and still popular theory embodies the basic intuition that what is best, or right is whatever makes the world best in the future because we cannot change the past, so worrying about the past is no more useful than crying over spilled milk. This general approach can be applied at different levels to different normative properties of different kinds of things, but the most prominent example is probably consequentialism about the moral rightness of acts, which holds that whether an act is morally right depends only on the consequences of that act or of something related to that act, such as the motive behind the act or a general rule requiring acts of the same kind[2]”. After the hacktivism group, Anonymous posted the video of how the high school boys were just laughing and practically making jokes about the assault that took place just then, it showed the gravity of the social climate around the topic of sexual assault in that town. The effects of this are that it gained an even larger media attention. In the short film, a woman mentioned that in that town, it is very hard to have a proper conversation about sexual assault. If someone wanted to speak about it in a conversation the other person would start to feel uncomfortable and just wanted to put the matter aside and forget about it and that was the end of it. Another person mentioned that the town was a very good town with devoted Christians in it. This already shows the division within the town. Some people want to get to the root of the issue and some people want to put it aside because that is not that big of an issue due to everyone’s religion. With the influx of media attention to the case at hand, it in a way forces the people of the town to not only discuss what is going on in there town, but it also makes it so the town cannot mess up pressing charges against the high school boys that assaulted the Jane Doe. Also, with the media attention, the effects it had on the townspeople were, to an extent, negative for a select few people. The inn where the video that was posted by Anonymous took place now has a negative connotation to it. The inn owner feels discouraged because he used his retirement money for it and now, he had reporters all around asking questions. In the age of media and online reviews, if a prospective customer is curious about the inn and decides to look it up, there would be an article that mentions that inn. The townspeople mentioned how they did not like the fact that they had outsiders coming to their town and creating “havoc” there. They feel as though they are being held hostage by 50,000 or so people and that they are dictating the narrative of the situation negatively. These people would probably think that it is not OK for outsiders to intervene. So, because of the media attention that Anonymous caused, the town is being affected negatively with all of the bad publicity. But on the flip side, women are able to speak up with a large amount of support that they would not have gotten otherwise. One lady recounts a time in her youth where she was assaulted and went to the deputy, but the deputy said “Oh, I know him”, and the prosecutor said that they were not going to take the case. Because of that she did not feel safe anywhere and lived life paranoid believing that she cannot depend on anyone, not even the police. She, and many others, believed that if Anonymous didn’t go there, then this would have been swept under the rug like plenty of other cases. So, these people believe that it is great that outsiders intervened here. With this newfound support group and with the amount of media attention, Anonymous was able to uplift women's voices and make sure the justice department did what they were supposed to do. Considering the effects of their actions, the good outweighs the bad and this would be deemed as ethical through consequentialism. The common trend you see with hacktivism is that hacktivist groups like Anonymous figured out how to use information in order to get the reaction they want. The main goal that they mentioned in the video was to “put the information out there and that the people are free to do whatever they want with that information[3]”. All Anonymous did was give the town a warning/heads up and that gave the people online the push they needed to do their digging and spread information that they had and that they could find on the public domain like Twitter. That is not “hacking” per se, but everything that happened afterward was almost like the domino effect. The group posted the video of the boys making light of the situation and that was almost like a smoking gun for the people. Whether or not they got that video legally or by hacking is not explicitly mentioned in the video, so it's hard to say what they did was illegal. But given that the effects were for the most part positive and it brought light to a situation that would have been swept under the rug just like the other cases, what the hacktivist group, Anonymous, did was ethical, based on consequentialism.

“The sleepy rustbelt town of Steubenville, Ohio, was once best known for high school sports and as the birthplace of Dean Martin. But when a teen sexual assault committed by two members of the football team surfaced, the shadowy hacker group Anonymous caught wind of the story and decided to intervene. After publishing videos and social media from the night of the assault to their millions of online followers, they sparked viral outrage and demands for #JusticeforJaneDoe. They unleashed a passionate mob, and their actions divided the small town, but in the process gave strength to generations of women forced to hide abuse. This film asks, when it seems like nothing will change, when is it OK for outsiders to intervene [1]?” My opinion is subjective depending on details and should be looked at on a case to case basis. I generally am anti-activist; this case is slightly different in the fact that there was video evidence of wrongdoing. What these kids did was not right or moral, and they seemed aware of their actions and even laughed at the idea. They were foolish kids. Anonymous’ first video about the situation elicited a response, an emotional response before any details or evidence were shown or discussed. Generally, I do not believe that large numbers grant validity to a topic and unwavering support of justice perpetuates war in my eyes. Back in the day we thought we were doing something divine by burning witches at stake, but we were simply killing people. There are consequences to tough cases like this where it is likely to have a divide of opinions. Some will have strong ties to their beliefs and have reasons for that, and some will follow. Many opinions will be swayed for the good and for the bad. You cannot dismiss or accept any of it at face value, because you cannot predict the intent. It takes a morally sound person to be aware of the situation at hand and accept the movements that are happening as a result even if you don’t agree with them or spread the issue if you do agree with them, either action will have consequences. The free thinker might be attacked for voicing their opinion by mobs that are no better than the people committing crimes. The person who has emotional ties to the situation at hand will raise awareness, which is positive, but they might perpetuate the divide. It is hard to say what which side outweighs the other, I believe the rise in awareness and the support from others should outweigh the oppositions opinions if you are the activist. In society we tend to push a perfect opinion on people between the media, social media, etc. That is not moral. A rise in awareness is a positive notion, it is the consequences that come out of it that tend to be negative But that does not immediately make one side more right about the situation, it just means they think a different way.
